Group F Final Project: Air Travel Analysis

Summary

We are looking to start-up a travel agency company based out of Queens, NY where the JFK Airport is located. Before opening our doors, we would like to find our ideal airline we would exclusively partner with. Since we are only just starting up, we would like to only focus on one travel destination to offer to our customers before we plan to grow as a company. We would like to narrow our initial search down to the top five traveled airports(LAX, ORD, ATL, DFW, and DEN). Our analysis consists of Regression, Graphs, Heat Maps, and Machine Learning.

Regression

Now that we have slimmed down the data that wed like to observe, we can look into which airline will be the best partner. We will start off by using simple regression to compare the airlines to see which ones are most likely to arrive on time (ArrDel15 = Arrive within 15 min of expected). This data is binary (0 means on time and 1 is arrival was delayed by at least 1 min) so the results will be a percent. From this first analysis, we can see that Alaska airlines is most likely to get there on time only arriving late to ~8% of their flights. After we wanted to analyze which airline was likely to cancel (Cancelled which is also binary). From that analysis, we can see that again, Alaska airlines is the front runner, canceling only about 1% of their flights. Therefore, we are confident in our choice to use Alaska Airlines for our preferred airline.

airlineRegress <- lm(formula=ArrDel15~Reporting_Airline, data=kennedySelected)

We did similar analysis for likelihood to arrive on time and likelihood to cancel for the five major airports as well. With these additional regressions, we found that Denver is most likely to have on time flights and Los Angeles is least likely to cancel. Los Angeles was the runner up for being most likely to have on time flights. From these regressions, we chose to offer LAX as the first travel location to our customers.

Because LAX wasnt the front runner for the arriving on time analysis, we wanted to dive deeper into which variables are most likely to cause delays in order to better predict delays for our customers. We again used the ArrDel15 as our dependent variable, but now we used multiple regression to have the day of the week, month, the departure delay time, if there was a weather delay, and if there was a carrier delay. We found that Weather delays and Carrier delays were not statistically significant (p value was too high). We then reran the multiple regression with just the significant variables to get the below output. We can see from the regression that the later in the week (Monday=1, Sunday=7) a flight is, the more likely it would arrive late. Conversely, the later in the year (January=1, December=12) a flight is, the less likely it would arrive late. Departure Delay is something that is significant, to be expected, but that is something that is a little out of our control. From this, we can encourage our customers to fly on a weekday and later on in the year to get the best chance at being not delayed.

multRegress = lm(formula = ArrDel15 ~ DayOfWeek + Month + DepDelay, data=kennedySelected)
summary(multRegress)

Map Analysis Support

To further back our findings with the regressions, we wanted to look at the data in a visual format. Given that flight data is geographic by nature, we decided to do a deep dive into maps to incur more conclusions

In the following code, we merged the us maps data, containing longitude and latitude with our Kennedy Selected data in order to plot and aesthetically manipulate the map by the 23 variables we decided to include.

Based on this map, we can see that LAX is receiving far more traffic than the other four airports. Atlanta and Chicago are following close behind, with Denver and Dallas/ Forth Worth receiving the least. This tells us that We need to prioritize airline flying into LAX, ATL, and ORD.

Based on this information, we were ready to then look at airline specific data and decide which of our 6 carriers was the best choice. These flight distributions support the conclusions we drew from our initial regressions. Given that LAX was the airport with the most incoming flights and the most airline partnerships, it confirmed our decision to keep LAX our our first destination. That decision allowed us to rule out Endeavor Air as a potential partner. We were also able to rule out American Airlines and Jet Blue as they had more equally distributed flight paths and we wanted to ensure we were partnering with an airline that would invest the most resources into LAX.

This left us to choose between United, Delta, and Alaska Airlines. Combined with the delay and cancellation statistics we saw in our regressions, we felt that the traffic flow map supported our Alaska Decision as they only fly to LAX from JFK. Therefore, we would have plenty of opportunities to re-book when flights inevitably get cancelled or delayed.

Heat Maps

Another factor that we chose to display visually was likelihood of a flight to be delayed on any given day of the week. In order to illustrate this in a way that airlines can be compared, we utilized a tiled heat map. The code below contains the process used to determine the unique airlines in our data set, to merge the lookup table containing human-readable airline names, and to clean the data of observations that contained an NA in the ArrDel15 observation.

Next the data was summarized in order to determine the percentage of late flights. Finally, before plotting the heatmap, the data was grouped by both airline name and day of the week and then summarized by dividing the number of flights by the mean arrival delay of each group.

The heatmap was plotted with a tile geometry with the day of the week on the X axis, the airline name on the Y axis, and was filled according to the percentage of flights that arrived at least 15 minutes late. The graph illustrated superior on-time performance by Alaska Airlines with the only exception being Thursday and Friday flights.

####Delays by DoW####

#Create copy of the data and make airline names human readable.
lateDoW <- kennedySelected

##   0.000   0.000   0.000   0.209   0.000   1.000
airlineDoW <- lateDoW %>%

  summarize(numb_flights = n(),

    geom_tile(aes(x = DayOfWeek, y = Airline_Name, fill = percent_delayed), color = 'black') +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7,9), labels = function(x){
    case_when(x == 1 ~ 'Monday', x == 2 ~ 'Tuesday', x == 3 ~ 'Wednesday', x == 4 ~ 'Thursday', x == 5 ~ 'Friday', x == 6 ~ 'Saturday', x == 7 ~ 'Sunday', x == 9 ~ 'Unknown')
  }) +
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = 'Spectral', labels = function(x) paste0(x*100, '%')) +
  labs(x = 'Day of the Week', y = 'Airline', fill = 'Delayed flights',
       title = 'Percentage of delayed flights by Day of the Week',
       subtitle = 'Averaged across 2021 for JFK Departures')+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        plot.caption = element_text(vjust = 7), axis.title.y = element_blank())

Machine Learning

We leveraged the JFK flight data and created a new data frame in order for us to create a machine learning model for probability of flight cancellation. Specific data points that were using are day of week, arrival city/airport, departure delay, arrival delay, carrier delay, weather delay and if the fight was ultimately cancelled or not. We used 70% of the data as our training data and 30% of the data for testing. Ultimately we were able to achieve 97.5% accuracy in our predicitve model. When we ran it against the confusion matrix the accuracy rate was fairly similar.

#Creating data frame

flightDelayData <- data.frame(DayofWeek=kennedySelected$DayOfWeek,
                         Airline=kennedySelected$Reporting_Airline,
                         ArrivalAirport=kennedySelected$Dest,
                         ArrivalCity=kennedySelected$DestCityName,
                         DepartureDelay=kennedySelected$DepDelay,
                         ArrivalDelay=kennedySelected$ArrDelay,
                         CarrierDelay=kennedySelected$CarrierDelay,
                         WeatherDelay=kennedySelected$WeatherDelay,
                         FlightCancel=as.factor(kennedySelected$Cancelled))

flightDelayData[is.na(flightDelayData)] <- 0

flightDelayData[flightDelayData < 0] <- 0
## Warning in Ops.factor(left, right): '<' not meaningful for factors
head(flightDelayData)
#Creating training and test data set

set.seed(2345)
training <- createDataPartition(y=flightDelayData$FlightCancel, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
trainingList <- flightDelayData[training,]
testList <- flightDelayData[-training,]

dim(trainingList)
## [1] 12649     9

## [1] 5420    9
#Build Model for Support Vector Machine (SVM)

trctrl <- trainControl(method="cv", number=2)


svm_FlightCancelled<- train(FlightCancel~., data= trainingList, method="svmRadial",
                   preProc= c("center", "scale"),
                   trControl=trctrl)
